useEffect is used for side effects in functional components. The dependency array controls when the effect runs:

```javascript
// Runs after every render
useEffect(() => {
  console.log('Every render');
});

// Runs only on mount
useEffect(() => {
  console.log('Mount only');
}, []);

// Runs when dependencies change
useEffect(() => {
  console.log('Count changed');
}, [count]);
```

That's a common mistake! If you use a value inside useEffect but don't include it in the dependency array, you'll have a stale closure. The effect will use the old value from when it was first created.

Example of the problem:
```javascript
const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

useEffect(() => {
  const timer = setInterval(() => {
    console.log(count); // Always logs 0!
  }, 1000);
  return () => clearInterval(timer);
}, []); // Missing count dependency
```

The fix:
```javascript
useEffect(() => {
  const timer = setInterval(() => {
    console.log(count); // Logs current value
  }, 1000);
  return () => clearInterval(timer);
}, [count]); // Include count
```

Great question! Cleanup functions are crucial for preventing memory leaks and unwanted side effects.

Return a cleanup function from useEffect to:
1. Cancel subscriptions
2. Clear timers
3. Remove event listeners
4. Abort API calls

Example:
```javascript
useEffect(() => {
  // Setup
  const subscription = api.subscribe();
  const timer = setTimeout(() => {}, 1000);
  window.addEventListener('resize', handler);

  // Cleanup
  return () => {
    subscription.unsubscribe();
    clearTimeout(timer);
    window.removeEventListener('resize', handler);
  };
}, []);
```

The cleanup runs:
- Before the effect runs again
- When component unmounts

Sure! Here's a real-world example of fetching data with cleanup:

```javascript
function UserProfile({ userId }) {
  const [user, setUser] = useState(null);
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);
  const [error, setError] = useState(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    let cancelled = false;

    async function fetchUser() {
      try {
        setLoading(true);
        const response = await fetch(`/api/users/${userId}`);
        const data = await response.json();

        if (!cancelled) {
          setUser(data);
          setError(null);
        }
      } catch (err) {
        if (!cancelled) {
          setError(err.message);
        }
      } finally {
        if (!cancelled) {
          setLoading(false);
        }
      }
    }

    fetchUser();

    // Cleanup: prevent state updates if component unmounts
    return () => {
      cancelled = true;
    };
  }, [userId]);

  if (loading) return <div>Loading...</div>;
  if (error) return <div>Error: {error}</div>;
  return <div>{user?.name}</div>;
}
```

Key points:
1. `cancelled` flag prevents state updates after unmount
2. Effect re-runs when `userId` changes
3. Previous fetch is cancelled before new one starts
